The main objectives of the Community Stewards WG are to provide visibility across all of the separate work streams such that all Stewards walk forward together in lockstep to reach our high level TEC goals. Our weekly meetings are a place to check-in on the temperature of the community, to resolve blockers, to raise questions that affect the Stewards or the members of our community and to solve them with collective intelligence. We are agile in our planning and follow a 2-week Sprint cadence.

Weekly sync agenda: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1VQNgAThqMLaQrF21uoQabWelnyJKLtX-TbqOl8kVb0Q/edit

!praise to @Griff (💜,💜) for taking on the Discord onboarding improvement issue and caring so much about it.
!praise to @eduardovegap for completing all Hatch content pieces.

Hi everyone, Nate and I had a meeting discussing the Content and Distribution Strategy. Here are the notes from our call. We will discuss it tomorrow on the weekly sync.

**Content Distribution Strategy Meeting (Nate/Marko)**

    •    Using Zenhub board in a brand new repo with established content distribution lifecycle (pipeline) https://github.com/TECommons/content-distribution#workspaces/tec-content-production-and-distribution-60549332d7d741001bbea827/board?repos=349409011
    •    Allow both internal and external contributors to easily submit Ideas and Requests for content distribution. Create a link that automatically opens New Issue on the board with a pre-defined template (issue template draft already created)
    •    Medium, Telegram, Forum, Discord (set up bots in between) Need to figure out who will build bots, whomanages them and how to propose edits whenever we need to address CD strategy  Who runs the bots? We want to propose a change. Where can we do that? / ask VyVy and Kris
    •    Medium: feature other projects within the TE community to publish on our platform and engage others to come to TE community
    •    Decide on a central place where all our resources and information can be found with instructions on how to do something (Gitbook, special page on our website, can be public and pass protected for internal resources) 
    •    We will need to have a person to PM the CD process, Nate volunteer to take it for starters but… 
    •    We need to think how to scale regular contributors!

messages.content: I agree with Sem.  People need to fully understand the implications of these types of voting decisions.  We can get away with low voter turnout if we KNOW that proper communication AND education on the topic was presented to the community effectively.   Also capturing the elements of what makes this decision worthy of a community vote is something we should evaluate.  If we consider this vote to be legitimate on the grounds of community education and awareness, I would say no, its not legitimate.

Thank you, @liviade, for questioning the unanimous yes vote. It's good that we are asking ourselves this. My yes vote was based on the following assumptions:
1. I have a high level understanding of the mechanics and advantages, enough to believe this is worth trying.
2. In the case a serious blocker surfaces, we can shift to an in-house method. 
3. Proposals by @sem(🌸,🐝)  carry additional weight for me, personally, because he is always so  thoughtful and analytical
3. Trust in Soft Gov, Gravity and Commons Swarm to execute this in the community's best interest.
It might be worth a "show of hands" how many of us have actually used Celeste? (I haven't depsite it being on my todo list for a while!)

Thanks for raising this question, Lívia. I can only speak to my own experience, but I would say I did not feel informed enough to vote (I'm ashamed!) but felt in a case like this, I would leave it to those more informed to make a good decision. I suppose that is a lazy mindset (I am sorry I did not manage better; "overwhelmed" is a better word than "lazy" here), and again it represents only my own! 😖
I have used it, but not completely since there hasn't been a celeste dispute on 1hive(*and thus I didn't get drafted as a keeper) as of yet.

thanks for all the answers to this! I like your point @sem(🌸,🐝) that the covenant process will be very informative and will ratify this vote 🙏 also agree with you @chuygarcia.eth, Including debates in most of our voting practices seems like the best way to go
and ditto @Vyvy-vi

messages.content:
The Association was chosen as the TEC legal strategy by the legal working group for a few reasons : 1. Liability is to cover every hatcher, someone not under legal protection could be a possible risk/liability. 2. The Trusted Seed ensures value aligned Hatchers and has a single process for everyone involved. It lowers the overhead and increases legitimacy to not open exceptions. 
It is a choice to participate in the hatch under this conditions and anyone can participate after the Commons Upgrade. The scholarships are offered so there is no block for any trusted member that wants to be involved. 
Here is most of our legal documentation https://app.gitbook.com/@token-engineering-commons/s/tec-handbook/hatch-101/legal

messages.content: any proposals on what to do?
I have a few...

#1 🚫👽 No Abnormal Intervention 👽🚫 
We call it in the call as we planned no matter how close the results are... Livia reloads live and boom thats the answer....

Various other options that i see we have and some can be mixed and matched:

#2 We follow the Disputable Voting pattern that we have in the Commons final arrangement... its called "wait for quiet" where if there is a flip in the final result in the last 24 hours, then there is 24 more hours extended for voters that havent voted yet.

#3 We extend it 24 hours and thats it

#4 We close the 2 issues that people voted on that are clearly out of the running

#5 We do a full runoff over the weekend, closing all votes and only putting up Fire and No Aliens

#6 We combine the votes for the 2 non-intervention and intervention (a horrible idea please lets not do this but i'm saying it anyway)
Any other mechanisms we should consider?

#7 We follow approximately what it is in the forum and Jeff and I hack out a final solution that is a combination of both proposals 

What I would propose is that ~50% impact hours from 🔥  is counted as people's IH and ~50% impact hours from 🚫👽 s counted as people's IH and the 2 amounts get added together. 

The 50% wouldn't be 50% but would be the % of votes that each proposal got.
@JeffEmmett would you be down for #7?

https://forum.tecommons.org/t/pre-hatch-impact-hours-distribution-analysis/376/50?u=liviade
There is a support for solution #7 here: 

**What if there is a polarized scenario, where 2 different proposals have an evenly split majority of votes in the run-off?**
(By evenly split, we consider a difference of less than 10 votes between first and second place.)
In this case, the top 2 authors will be invited to a hack session to merge their proposals together and commit to a collaborative result.

- My bad for putting 10 votes there. I wish I had added a larger margin because we are still gonna be polarized even with 100 or 200 votes splitting first and second place
1 3 and 5 looks good to me
It will be a dream if we can come up with a collaborative result after such a long and demanding process for everyone 💛
what is 13 and 5?

#1 🚫👽 No Abnormal Intervention 👽🚫 
We call it in the call as we planned no matter how close the results are... Livia reloads live and boom thats the answer....
Various other options that i see we have and some can be mixed and matched:
#3 We extend it 24 hours and thats it
#5 We do a full runoff over the weekend, closing all votes and only putting up Fire and No Aliens
🔥  do not represent me at all

any collaboration would start by paying all the work done to all the members who didnt get paid even if being working full time/half time it dosent matter and not just burning and saying this is the best for the commons coz its not.
it was a process for almost a year

I think that the polarization shown is not going to change by extending the votes, because its a reflection of polarized positions around the community. I think that if we choose any of the proposals like they are, there will be a lot of conflict around legitimacy and there will be people feeling good but also there will be people feeling bad about the decision. 

I like #7 as proposes a dialogue to not foster polarization, i think we should try to flip this into a win-win escenario, and not a splitting decision.
I don't like #7 because we were voting proposals, not representatives
+1!! The most genius solutions come from the meeting of polarizations
both top proposals are a signal. We can't ignore that a large part of the community will be unsatisfied with one or another result. So why not looking for the optimal outcome for all?

I would love to hear from all @Stewards :
1- Do you agree with a non-polarized, collaborative approach and believe this is the best for the Commons? 
2- If you don't agree, what is the benefit for taking a polarized choice and how this can benefit the Commons?

1. Yes with disclaimer.
The initial proposal and approach were fundamentally polarizing.

1. I agree. And the suggestion of combining both proposals into one(or to collaborate into a joint solution in between authors) is the road to go, so we will ending up integratin the majority of the community intentions and votes.

Honestly, I believe that this whole process of now trying to change something backwards has added more conflict than benefit. I just do not see any option where at least someone will not feel confortable with. There is no perfect solution because there are many different cases. No matter what you do, some people will feel not being treated fair. I believe we should try to "compensate" looking forward and not backward. For instance adding the governance power and adding some IH to those members we believe they deserve some, but not taking IH from those who have them. Adding is fair, taking away is not, no matter if the system was not perfect, they did not design the system and were playing the rules.
I agree with Santi
There is really no taking away. I think this is a misconception. Who would be taking what from who?
My job would be deleted  and many others too
i pass from 600+ IH to 200
if u are telling me after almost a year i only worked 200hours well ok
the good thing on jeff proposal its we only have 10k of IH so the formula would be ok and the parameters would be represented
I think non-transferable governance tokens make no sense
and not to talk the damage that does to the cultural build
And don't get me wrong, I thing Jeff proposal is very very well defined and fair, but only if it adds to those who are not well represented, not if it takes away.
i do not agree with you santi its not fair

your job is definitely not gonna be deleted. Your work is very appreciated in the community, so does everyone else's work. The problem that is being pointed lies in the distribution lines. So how many times one person was more compensated than others. In terms of governance power and capital power.
the goal on jeff proposals its to be on the top group not to do the best job  since we are all equal whats the point on being more efficient
well ya thats why i said the first point to get an agreement its to get people who was not paid, paid
do you imagine using saving during all that time and then have a decision that saids you only get 200ih becuase its good for the commons (and again its not)

Livi, if you go to the grocery store and they have a product with the wrong price, and you do not realize and go to the cashier and then, they tell you the price is double, what do you do? you tell them the price labeled was the one you saw, they charge you the initial price and then they change it because they where wrong and it should be changed, but always looking ahead not backwards. Now I believe there is an in between solution adding to those who deserve it and where not well represented, actually I think that is fair, the same way we where "tweeking" the IH at the very last moment in every distribution when we where seeing the result was not fair enough, but always adding.

The Cultural Build is an experiment of a collaborative and self managed organization which is implementing Ostrom's 8 principles into our culture.  We are doing something for the first time. We have always taken the posture of looking into how things are moving, and if change is needed, change can be proposed. The results of this analys and votes are surfacing so many behavioral challenges that we still need to learn how to navigate. We can't have a set in stone tradition before even launching. There is a need for flexibility when in experimental grounds
I see your analogy is coming from a market perspective. And that is the intrinsic problem we are dealing with. We can't be talking about market price of a token that doesn't exist yet

I am not saying I am not open to change, but always adding to those who where not treated fair by the system looking at the overall final distribution, just tweeking it as we where doing every other week. Then, learn from all this experience and improve it for the future
are you sure?

I'm sorry you were using your savings to participate in the DAO. I don't know where that message came along but financial stability was never offered by Impact Hours. It is actually a loss for the DAO if members cash out most of their tokens. So I think there was a misunderstanding in how things were communicated
well ofc and if the IH were worth 0 everything would be fine
the problem here its at the end of the game when everything its done

Just look at the voting system right now. We are using a voting process and then when we see two options quite close in votes, we decide we need to change the overall result to take into account those not voting the winning proposal. I am not against that, but we are changing the rules again just because we do not feel the outcome is fair. When you vote using a voting process, you respect the rules in that process, if you do not like the final outcome you then decide if you feel represented in the community and decide what you want to do as a member and as a community, you decide if you want to change the process in cases where the top options are almost tied in votes, but you do not change the result of the voting, the voting process should not be changed in that decision, it should be changed afterwards for future voting.
the voting process its also not accurate why trusted seed have to decide what IH are worth?

we are not changing the rules. The original post with the guidelines mentions the possibility of a polarized vote https://forum.tecommons.org/t/pre-hatch-impact-hours-distribution-analysis/376/50?u=liviade
ok, then I am wrong, appologyze for that Livi
we are just investigating how to have an approach that will be healthier for the whole and not carry out damages from a polarized community.
no worries. The post does say we will have a collaborative option if there is a difference of 10 votes. Which was my mistake to put such a little slippage considering how many votes were cast total
so I was just wondering if we would like to proceed to a collaborative approach anyways, or if we will take the winner even if the difference is a little more than 10 votes

Anyway, my final take is to add to those cases where the system has not been fair, I feel absolutely happy with that option as long as none of the IH already distributed is taken away, the final result is probably the same because at the end it is the relative amount what counts, but it is just the way of doing things what is important more than the final result for every single one of us.

absolutely. I didn't understand there was a proposal to take IH away. but considering we have a limited percentage that goes to the builder pool based on the params decision, minting more tokens to others will naturally redistribute the values but I might be missing something here
not really
with the actual params more IH =  bigger cultural tribute we should re-do params

Some people have IH taken away in Praisemageddon..

I think it would be a lot easier to discuss this if we could ignore the outcome a bit and as Santi says, look ahead.

Right now, no proposal has a majority of votes. not even close... the top voted proposal has ~40%.

This has been a horrible horrible experience for our community. I regret that we even debated this. I really do. 

We have an extremely polarized community right now. This shit is like democrats vs republicans in the states, it's gross. :RainbowPuke: 

We have to think about what is best for the Commons. 

#7 allows everyone to win a little bit, which is just the best that we can do right now. Instead of a clearly defined set of winners and losers, we can have both sides opinions represented in the final outcome. 

Honestly, this whole time I have been watching this as a train wreck waiting to happen, i never saw a way to push the car off the track...

Amazingly, I think we can actually "Split the baby in half" and it will work out. (google it if you don't know what i'm talking about)

I have had a lot of anxiety about this, and when Livia brainstormed with me and this idea popped out, it was the first time in weeks that i felt hope around this topic. That we could actually have a solution that doesnt completely just disregard a large swath of our community. 

I'm not happy about an intervention at all, I never thought it was a good idea, we should have clearly laid out the rules in advance if we wanted to do that and then stuck with them IMO it's too late to change the rules and decide to take from some to give to others. But that is not everyone's opinion and I really love that we have a community of diverse opinions. 

Looking forward, COMPROMISE is a value that will hold us together better than accepting the vile, false dichotomies of democrat vs republican, socialist vs libertarian, Good vs bad, right vs wrong.

There is no "good" here, there is no "right" here. There is only best... 

Compromise is something I think we as a community can be proud of, and it is at the very least in the spirit of the rules as set forth for this process, if not explicitly defined as the solution for a polarized outcome.
Sorry for the rant... I will also post in the forum
I propose that this conversation be had in a public channel i.e. Soft Gov
since this decision affects the larger community, not only the stewards
for transparency
This is a public channel i think
yeah this is a public channel to all that have joined the discord
Okay great, I wasn't sure thanks

The community is split, and democracy is about listening to voices - if we choose a "polar" decision, this is basically saying that we don't want to listen to half of our community, regardless of "which side" of the debate you are on or your personal opinion. But actually, if we look at how many individuals are supporting, it is not really "half" the community as individuals as Tam pointed out in her analysis. I propose we look at how many individuals supported each proposal to have further data for consideration. The vote was about reducing the whale power in the system, but the vote itself is using the whale allocation which is at the center of the debate.

Tam and myself suggested  one person, one vote in the beginning of the discussion as otherwise, the issue of contention that we are voting on, is affected by the Token log process - as pointed out in our general decision space and governance discussions in the last Soft Gov meeting. Livia raised the issue of identity and not using 1p1v on the forum, but there was still some differing views surrounding this. In my opinon, using token weighted voting did not and does not make sense, when the issue of contention is token distribution.

Should 4 people in our community have more weight than the rest of the community combined? It feels like the 1%. We are trying to create better systems here. This doesn't feel like my economy, my choice. It feels like the choice of 4 or 5 people.
what i voted as an ih whale its on third place all my votes where there i wonder what are u talking about

This is a clear case of post-truth. 5 people do not control 50% of the votation. Period. Please refer to the original forum post, or my last reply here: https://github.com/CommonsBuild/IH-intervention/issues/13
You deserve to be rewarded Zepti. There is no question how hard you worked. It's about how much, and is it several times more than others, who did similar amounts of work.
And it's not personal.
yeah i know
You could change anyone's name here and it would be the same.
Zargham always says "governance is a dumpster fire" - this is all an experiment. We cannot change the past, but we have a choice now.

For me the basic question, regardless of rules/systems/processes is: do we want to have a whale type allocation, or do we want people who all put in a lot of work in various ways, to govern together? Does anyone feel "entitled" to 2/3/4/5x than others. If so, it is hard for me to want to participate in a community where this mentality is present and overrules the more collective governance allocation.
I would happily "give" away my IHs to others. I wish this was the common sentiment and would make me feel much better in investing further in this community.
And that is just how I feel. Nothing personal to anyone.
I was a kindergarten teacher in a past life. And sharing is a very basic principle for me as I want to look out for others, not just myself.
We all work hard but when we work together, we create more value to be shared.
Would you mind share with me the salary of your last 9 month? i didnt get paid at all :/
we did similar work
Sure I would if we were talking about splitting equally. I'm not. I think you should get more.
Because of course, that wouldn't be fair.

"We propose awarding unpaid contributors a 50% bonus on their awarded Impact Hours over those who were compensated $100/day for their work (the typical remuneration rate for a TEC contributor)."
There is no easy answer. I actually don't love either top proposal as both will have challenges.
So what is the common ground? What can we agree on? And start there.
Sounds like we are agreeing (at least me and you Zepti ;D) on that people who didn't get paid should get more - awesome! I think probably most of the community would agree on that.
Maybe we start with what is agreed, and build on that.
actually its very hard

(Also I only worked full-time for TEC from October-February. there is a debate happening in the soft gov channel if someone wants to participate in the discussion we are having right now

messages.content: Hi @solsista there is a "WG readiness for Hatch" checklist and zenhub list that we've been tracking in the Stewards call for the past few weeks and sharing in the weekly Community sync. It is to highlight all the remaining issues that would **block **us from Hatching! Since 0mega does not have any Hatch blocking issues, I defaulted it to ready. When we started tracking there were a number of working groups that were not yet ready: Community Stewards, Soft Gov, Hatch Outreach, Comms, TEC Params, Commons Swarm, Legal and Labs. And so these were really where all the focus went. Week by week the ready signals were given and now, as @liviade mentioned above, the last remaining task is the final IH list! Hey @Tamarandom , you were asking for project managers on your wish list.

I've done some work with @anna-marie , so that's one point of reference.

I'm also just on Graviton Training, Cohort 2, and loving what you guys are doing, with specific issues I want and need to resolve. 

In the corporate world, I was project manager of an end to end product and service delivery supply chain where we added 100,000 customers at a major UK Telco over two years.

I tended not to use Kanban, because I feel that project participants need "their own channels" structured using their own language. But then relating each channel, so channels don't become silos. I see that here!

That approach, plus a consultative  / collaborative mindset, meant a much higher than average success rate. That could have been luck, or some kind of instinct, but it felt right.

My challenge has been and still is to adapt that to open, diverse networks eg in Twitter and Discord.

Luckily, I love learning. Also luckily, there's so much to learn here. I can already see Gravity WG applications in other DAOs.

I'm like a kid in a sweety shop!

How shall we engage from here?

**Human Verification Proposal**

With discord's new features and how they have been developing(ephemeral messages and interactions, slash commands), a new verification workflow is possible, which makes it safer to do it right inside discord and make it more intuitive, so that anyone could join without much issues :)

```md
## What is this?
New users enter the sever, and they need to agree to the rules at the screen that pops up before they could do things in the server.

After that they will have to click on a button in `#verification`, and select an answer from the dropdown. If they answer correctly, the bot assignes a "human" or "verified" role to them

## The cons of using this -
- This might not work for people with outdated discord clients, since this was added like 3-4 months ago. (*though, discord auto-updates, and is usually up-to-date for most people*)
- If anyone gets stuck, they'll have to DM someone to get access. (We would need some people who would be interested in assigning people the 'human'/'verified' role, if they're stuck)
- Random errors could crash the bot (this isn't pitch perfect as of yet, since my friend(https://github.com/nhcarrigan) like made this new bot in 30-40 mins).

## The Pros of this -
- Waaaay better than the captcha site. The user experience in this method is super smooth, and ensures that joining isn't a hassle.
- One solution, instead of a split-solution. (the captcha site was a site, plus a bot)
- This is cooool!
- Unifies the rules-agreement and the verification into one source, rather than needing to react to a message by CarlBot.
- UserSafety and Privacy ++
  This won't need people to use discord auth to sign up(which can be slightly scary for a few people).
  Nothing get's stored by this, and all data is contained between discord, due to which we won't need to make legal Terms of Service and Usage documents
```

Here's a video showing the walkthrough -

@Stewards Snapshot params open for voting on Snapshot 👆

What would this look like if was simple? 

We already have one nomination for the complete multisig. It's just one nomination. Let's get more. The rationale behind the nomination was explained. Cool. That's helpful for the community to understand and vote on. Why not have an open call to the community to submit “nomination sets” and explain their reasons why?  Then 2-3 or even 5-6 people or even more people spend the time to consider what rationale is important to them for this responsibility. Then they find the 7 persons that match that criteria, reach out to ask and explain and, if all agree, they submit that nomination set. Then we have a group of nomination sets. And we vote on them. 

A monimation set if a group of 7 persons that each:
- Hold one or more TECH tokens
- Understand and agree to the responsibilities of the role

The responsibilities of the role are (This is an off the cuff draft and can be improved):
- Respond within 24 hours of a request to use the multisig.
- Verify the allocation request was passed by the community (specifying exactly how would be useful here. For the present, let’s say it’s comparing the snapshot vote and the parameters required to pass.)
- Alert the other multisig holders when you will be unavailable for a 24h or greater period of time
- Uphold the values of the TEC
- Spread joy (this is not actually a really real responsibility but it sure would be nice).
i don't see that nominating sets will be any simpler, maybe even more complicated than a ranked choice voting of individuals
looking in the long run if we can sort out this process we can set the standard for picking multisigs in the future

I dont like to create groups it also split between "political values" the community, you either choose this or that (or the strategic middle idc). I mean is not so bad if anyone one can propose but i feel rank choice voting on idividuals will give us a better represented multisig according to what the community wants

You know, @Zeptimus , you and and I might have different points of view on a coupla things but where we always align is that it’s in the hands of the community to decide. 🙂 🙌🏽 

In this case, it looks like the community should probably have a say in how a group is selected for __community multisigs__ (differentiated from the multisigs of WGs).  Especially as this may not only set a precedent but may be **The** protocol moving forward. 

There are at least 3 options so far: (1) individuals nominate or self-nominate and then they are listed in a rank choice vote, (2) individuals nominate a group from all token holders (and do the leg work of assuring there is consent and share their rationale for the nomination so the voting community can make an informed decision) and (3) individuals nominate a group from the Steward group.

The main objective of the Community Stewards WG is to provide visibility across all of the separate work streams such that all Stewards walk forward together in lockstep to reach our high level TEC goals. Our weekly meetings are a place to check-in on the temperature of the community, to resolve blockers, to raise questions that affect the Stewards or the members of our community and to solve them with the collective intelligence. We follow a Scrum framework and have a 2-week Sprint cadence.

Discussions happen on #stewards channel
All calls happen on #stewards voice channel

Sprint Retrospective: Every other Thursday at 6pm CET

I am voicing here and cross-posted in the Comms channel -  I feel it is not appropriate to use Twitter from the voice of a "decentralized DAO/Commons" to promote proposal/objectives (be political). Will Tweets go out to urge to pass *every proposal? Notification of proposals is important to keep people up to date, but showing favoritism or saying "this is our objective" is basically saying that every person in the TEC has this perspective, which again, I think is not the right use of this platform. Thank you for your consideration and would love to hear feedback.
Thanks Jess, I raised the same concern and this is already in the attention of the comms team 🙏🏾

A clear example of "co-opting" as political scientists would put it. When factions within wider rivalrous structures appraise common resources (in this case comms channels) to lobby in their favour. 

I'd say this is reminiscent of the "rewards discussion" or previous dismemberment of agreements made on rewards distribution before the hatch. Just saying because the TEC as an organic structure will continue to mimic its own flaws.

Hi @JessicaZartler and thank you for raising this. It is an important point. This tweet was flagged as an issue, acknowledged and understood to be an honest mistake. The subsequent tweet about a proposal took an objective tone. 🙏🏽

🙏I need some help!🙏

I'm trying to build a bridge between DAOs and Liberating Structures community, basically through the TEC. 

I think these two scenes are extraordinarily value aligned, can offer bananas value to one another and I like it when my friends meet each other!

In particular I am hosting a call as an introduction on Sunday 20 March that I'd like to invite you folks in particular and everyone from the TEC who's interested. 

We'll be exploring the opportunity space of how Liberating Structures can help DAOs with trust and coordination and how organizing as a DAO could help the LS scene.

https://qiqochat.com/e/ZorUTMqONuvhqRTrURMAFjvEN

Come to the event!
Help me get the word out!
Advice and counsel!
Feedback on these docs: what is least clear? 
How can I green pill these facilitation nerds?

Who's coming with me?!

want to share this fragment of a chapter about copyright CC and peer production licences: 
"A copyfarleft license must allow commons-based commercial use while denying the ability to profit by exploiting wage labour. The copyleft Non-Commercial approach does neither, it prevents commons-based commerce, while restricting wage exploitation only by requiring the exploiters to share some loot with the so-called original author. In no way does this overcome the iron law for either the authors or other workers. ‘Non Commercial’ is not a suitable way to describe the required endogenic/exogenic boundary. Yet, no other commons license exists that provides a suitable legal framework for commons-based producers to use. Only a license that effectively prevents alienated property and wage labour from being employed in the reproduction of the otherwise free information commons can change the distribution of wealth.
Interestingly, this is the correct application of the original institution of the commons, which was strictly related to material production (even reiterating this characteristic in today’s cultural debate sounds grotesque to many). The commons were land used by a specific community to harvest or breed their animals. If someone could not send cows to pasture and produce milk on it, it would not be considered a real commons. Kleiner argues that if money cannot be made from it, a culturalwork does not belong to the commons: it is still private property." 
Matteo Pasquinelli https://www.academia.edu/1992023/Animal_Spirits_A_Bestiary_of_the_Commons

I just want to compliment what @divine_comedian said with the problems of the transcription
- quantification periods are time sensitive, if 2 weeks of community call praise are dished at the same time, they will appear to belong to the same period and this is causing confusion to quantifiers. 
- @Manuel Flores expressed a lack of motivation to do this task, which I think we can all agree to be tedious. He also said it's a non-rewarded task - you can speak more on it Manu, but it's important for us to look at how people are feeling about what they are doing 
- so it's an unpleasant task that represents a single point of failure for a large data set 
- + the point that Mitch brought up, the praise people dish when they are on a rush has been quite low quality and generalized
but we don't want to lose the beauty and excitement and high vibes the praise round has in the community call, so how could we slowly request that people type their praise, and be more mindful of it?
@Griff (💜,💜)
@Tamarandom

we do the out-loud praise in the Giveth Community call but *also* everyone writes it in the channel. I think we could have a transition period where we just encourage that, but still have Algene (for example) as a backup for new people or people who forget, and then just phase out the idea that someone will be writing it down for you.
I write my call praise anyway, but just... not in the channel. I think a lot of people do this.
Hey Team! FYI I'll be out most of the day tomorrow, April 29

Maybe we can treat call praise as a "feeler" of sorts, that gives people space to voice out the praise, but there's no guarantee or expectation of transcription? (though, we transcribe the praise from the recording whenever there's a praise audit or praise analysis to see if someone's praise slipped through the cracks)
Yep!

Accomplish more with less. Constraints breed resourcefulness, self-sufficiency, and invention. There are no extra points for growing headcount, budget size, or fixed expense.

done!

Hey @Stewards !

I'm loving the Proposal Inverter, I've had ideas on this for a while.

I'm very much in favour of anything that helps DAOs to move across to systems that support good ideas, and the Proposal Inverter is a Rolls Royce of a solution, which will generate lots of data.

It is possible, though, to get a much simpler VW Beetle version in the short term, creating a Notion table, and showing a proposal moving through the following stages and statuses:

Idea ➡️ Team ➡️ Proposal ➡️ Project ➡️ Product ➡️ Data

The Notion would point to eg Google Drives where related documentation for that stage can be stored.

Why do this and not just wait for the Rolls Royce to show up?

Getting into the mindset early would be an advantage to all DAO members, because the effect of defining and publicising project roles and so forth is an important skill set, and can be developed with either variety of tool, although I acknowledge the PI will offer stepped stages, probably meaning greater accessibility to more folk, and substantial quantities of data, which of course then has intrinsic value for research.

I'd be interested to discuss this more with a TEC steward.

Heyy, thank you for the comment! Actually we are using kind of VW Beetle in proposal inverter’s development. Thanks to @ygg_anderson ‘s  initiation we embraced the dogfooding building model (a product built by the idea of the product). We are using excel sheets to mimic proposal inverter mechanism through off chain interactions. This video may help understand our building Philosophy:
https://youtu.be/x2gf-UUiEL0

messages.content:
I just got a message from someone I used to work with who happens to be a Hatcher. They were asking me why the TEC is asking for more money from them. Here's what they said (I got their permission to share this):

So why do you want more money from us?
or maybe I don't "get" what is going on but I felt like I did all this work to contribute like $1000+ to the hatch - and I could bearly do it with metamask etc - (and gosh I really hope I still have the keys etc - cause you know crypto and normal people and normal UX don't go really well together).  - why would I be asked for more money " to stay a member" I thought I "bought" into a DAO - was new to me that some how I could get degraded out - when I "bought" the tokens.

I asked them to forward the message they had received and it was an email. See attached. 

We have to be careful about these kinds of messages. I know that we're (justifiably) excited about the ABC, but this message left at least one person very confused. It also negatively impacted their impression of the TEC. In this case, it happens to be someone who is fairly influential in the broader open source world beyond Web3.

This email came on the heels of a request for Trusted Seed membership payments too, so that is exacerbating the problem and adding to real confusion:
-----
mmm...
i guess I am confused
So what did I "buy" membership in? or how do these relate - are they related?

I guess I was confused cause I didn't really track they were two different things - since I was walked through what I needed to do to join/buy tokens...
then I'm like "why am I being shaken down for money"

This left a really bad taste for the TEC with this person. I just happen to have known them, so they reached out to me to find out what this was. 

When we send messages to token holders, it's really important to first run them by others as part of the advice process. That's what we did with the update to token holders a few weeks ago, and it made the message way stronger. I'm always willing to have a look at stuff like this before it goes out (and I'm sure there are others who'd be willing to as well). This is especially true when the message is going to token holders. We're working so hard to bolster the connection with them; the last thing we want to do is confuse or alienate them.
Tbh, I did not know Trusted Seed was a yearly membership until I started getting messages about renewal. I have also seen this on #🦾｜help :

Hey @natesuits !

Great meeting yesterday thanks!

I tried to use the praise bot but it doesn't much like Android. Or my phone at any rate.

I wanted to respond to that conversation, and to give you an idea of how this can look, in fact how doable this can be.

TEC NEED
Unburden stewards from having to pick up everything about new arrivals in channel, or through resource draining live meetings, through a structured onboarding process that I'm calling Guild in a Box.

PROCESSES
There are two main processes

1️⃣ Contributor Pathway (see Discord screen shot, bottom six entries)

And then

2️⃣ Ideas Pathway (see Commonwealth screen shot, items 1-7 in LH column)

Both these structures are progressional, one state follows on from the other, and can be referred to easily in documentation so that new visitors find it easy to navigate and find their way to the subject areas that interest them.

The beauty here is the simplicity of the solution, which makes the UX so much easier to understand and support.

This is what I'm suggesting will begin to lift the burden on busy stewards trying to run currently three separate DAOs.

Given activity seems to be high in TEA, and low in CSTK and TEC, the suggestion is that onboarding in TEA could help relieve pressure on stewards the most in that setting, given you have @ 2000 new cats there to herd.

Now some folk will understand that some of the long term expertise will come from understanding how best to transition from one state to the next.

Given the app building skills here in TEC, it could also be an App, but I do want to assert my rights to the Intellectual Property in this, even though I don't know how that works in a Web 3/Commons setting.

Advice from TEC would be welcome, but I think this is something that can work in any DAO, and that perhaps a good number would be interested in, especially if I get Bankless on the case, with their strong media profiles.

messages.content:
I don't have any comment on the existing reflection on Comms but I'd observe Drucker's Rule - **you can't manage what you don't measure** so my question to stewards is what is measured to judge the performance of comms? is it
- (new) observers -> member
- time wasted search (outdated) TEC handbook
- new discord guests per week?
- sourceCred edge flows ??
- newsletter links clicked???
- time between observer and joining a TEAcademy course?

So I ask **think hard about user journey** then decide what measure , then perhaps repurpose comms (active/passive/bot-help). This is the **WHY-WHAT-HOW** pattern.

PS what's measured may not be important, what's important might not be measurable
(eg quality of twitter visitors might be more significant than traffic volume)

PPS SourceCred is way underutilised ... it's somewhat objective (legal haton ... avoids accusation of discrimination on the most squeaky wheel) and measures some stuff already

Option 1.  Cancel it
